1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:12,059
[music] At night, sometime around one o’clock, in a small provincial town without a defined name

2
00:00:12,059 --> 00:00:18,480
a young man, about 27 years old or so, enters a solitary wooden wing out in the yard—to visit

3
00:00:18,480 --> 00:00:24,000
a construction engineer, who is sitting on a sofa with a latticed back and hard leather

4
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:30,900
cushions. Almost immediately, he notices a plate on the windowsill with an untouched boiled chicken

5
00:00:30,900 --> 00:00:37,800
My name is Armen Zakharian, and this is Armen and Fyodor’s literary channel. Today we are launching a new section

6
00:00:37,800 --> 00:00:42,600
called “Episode.” Each time, we’ll closely examine just one

7
00:00:42,600 --> 00:00:47,820
fragment from the pages of world literature and analyze why this episode is special—

8
00:00:47,820 --> 00:00:54,180
special, and how what we call “art” functions within it. For our first attempt at this,

9
00:00:54,180 --> 00:01:01,800
we have chosen one of the most disturbing yet fascinating scenes from Dostoevsky’s novel “Demons.” It’s an episode almost

10
00:01:01,800 --> 00:01:08,760
at the very end of the book, in its concluding part. There, a certain Verkhovensky comes by night to the house of

11
00:01:08,760 --> 00:01:16,619
one Kirillov, and sees a chicken boiled with rice on the windowsill. And though right next to the chicken lies

12
00:01:16,619 --> 00:01:25,439
a loaded pistol, in this scene it is not the gun, but the chicken that plays the role of Chekhov’s gun, which is about

13
00:01:25,439 --> 00:01:30,540
to go off. But to understand what this shot is, and at whom it’s aimed, we need to

14
00:01:30,540 --> 00:01:37,740
first figure out who these two are, and how the two of them ended up here, together in the wing, at night,

15
00:01:37,740 --> 00:01:42,240
in the same room. It’s remarkable how, even at the very beginning of the book, just as he introduces the characters,

16
00:01:42,240 --> 00:01:51,600
Dostoevsky is already paving the way for this horrific nighttime encounter between them. Kirillov—a young man, about 27,

17
00:01:51,600 --> 00:02:00,119
Verkhovensky—almost a mirror image, a young man of about 27 or so. This deliberate similarity, of course,

18
00:02:00,119 --> 00:02:07,740
only underscores how deep the differences between them run. Kirillov is a vivid representative of that famous line of Dostoevsky’s fanatics,

19
00:02:07,740 --> 00:02:15,060
heroes who become passionately obsessed with some idea, start serving this idea, living for

20
00:02:15,060 --> 00:02:24,780
this idea. Only Kirillov’s plan is different—he intends, in the name of his idea, to die. Kirillov is obsessed with the notion of the God-man.

21
00:02:24,780 --> 00:02:30,420
He arrives at it by pondering the dilemma that the literature of this period, the second half

22
00:02:30,420 --> 00:02:38,220
of the nineteenth century, often struggled to resolve: how can one live after rejecting God? Suppose God no longer exists. Suppose we

23
00:02:38,220 --> 00:02:46,860
no longer believe in him. We, to use Verkhovensky’s term, have “written him off.” But the need to fill

24
00:02:46,860 --> 00:02:52,500
the emptiness left in his place—that need remains. And while another Dostoevsky character, in the same

25
00:02:52,500 --> 00:02:58,860
“Demons,” says: “If there is no God, then what kind of captain am I?”, Kirillov says,

26
00:02:58,860 --> 00:03:06,500
If there is no God, then I can take his place. Remember how Grebenshchikov sang: “You feel

27
00:03:06,500 --> 00:03:13,200
the draft from the vacancy in that place.” Kirillov feels just that very draft

28
00:03:13,200 --> 00:03:19,019
and formulates a terrible, insane thought—a thought he then falls in love with. “If

29
00:03:19,019 --> 00:03:23,760
a person,” he says, “resolves of his own will, for no reason—not out of anger,

30
00:03:23,760 --> 00:03:30,060
not out of fear, not out of malice, but solely and simply because he has the right—to depart from life,

31
00:03:30,060 --> 00:03:36,900
then, Kirillov reasons, in taking this step he will regenerate all of humanity and himself become a God-man.

32
00:03:36,900 --> 00:03:47,040
But there have already been millions of suicides, he’s told. “But none—none did it for this reason, not out of fear or for that purpose!” Kirillov retorts.

33
00:03:47,040 --> 00:03:52,799
And this crazy logic of his strikingly recalls an episode from

34
00:03:52,799 --> 00:03:57,420
“Don Quixote.” Remember, when the audacious, delusional Quixote tells Sancho Panza that

35
00:03:57,420 --> 00:04:04,019
one should imitate the famous knights of the past and go mad. The pragmatic Sancho then asks: “But,

36
00:04:04,019 --> 00:04:10,980
Señor, do you actually have a reason for going mad? What’s the reason?” — “Therein

37
00:04:10,980 --> 00:04:15,599
lies the point,” Don Quixote answers. “That’s precisely the peculiarity of my

38
00:04:15,599 --> 00:04:20,519
undertaking: whoever among the wandering knights went mad for some reason

39
00:04:20,519 --> 00:04:29,460
—such a one does not merit reward nor thanks. The trick is to lose one’s mind without any reason at all.”

40
00:04:29,460 --> 00:04:36,180
And as we’ll soon see, these parallels in the words of Kirillov and Quixote are far from accidental.

41
00:04:36,180 --> 00:04:41,820
So, to fulfill his mad idea, Kirillov has a loaded revolver on the windowsill, next to the chicken.

42
00:04:41,820 --> 00:04:46,680
You might ask: “So what is he waiting for? Why

43
00:04:46,680 --> 00:04:55,740
doesn’t he carry out his intention, if, after all, he needs no reason for it?” Here is where his nighttime

44
00:04:55,740 --> 00:05:01,680
visitor comes in—a revolutionary and nihilist, Pyotr Stepanovich Verkhovensky. This character

45
00:05:01,680 --> 00:05:07,080
is completely different, an extraordinary figure—funny and terrifying at the same time,

46
00:05:07,080 --> 00:05:14,340
comically and parodically, frighteningly loquacious and theatrical, but also terrifying, because he’s ready for any evil.

47
00:05:14,340 --> 00:05:22,259
Verkhovensky, yes, to some extent resembles Mephistopheles, but Mephistopheles had a better sense of humor, and

48
00:05:22,259 --> 00:05:29,820
by virtue of life experience and age, he was more restrained. But the most crucial thing is that they are fundamentally different. Verkhovensky

49
00:05:29,820 --> 00:05:35,220
is a supremely practical person. He believes the end justifies any means, and

50
00:05:35,220 --> 00:05:40,199
having encountered Kirillov with his ideological suicide project, Verkhovensky immediately

51
00:05:40,199 --> 00:05:45,660
figures out how to put this to good use—not for the regeneration

52
00:05:45,660 --> 00:05:52,380
of humanity—he couldn’t care less about that—but for his own demonic business. He decides

53
00:05:52,380 --> 00:05:56,940
to carry out a political assassination—and since Kirillov is utterly indifferent to

54
00:05:56,940 --> 00:06:04,820
when or how he dies, to have him write a confession to the murder before his death, thus using Kirillov’s death

55
00:06:04,820 --> 00:06:10,620
as an alibi for his own crime. So, this is the setup

56
00:06:10,620 --> 00:06:18,539
at the moment of their nocturnal meeting: a conflict of the spiritual (however sick; Don Quixote was mad, too)

57
00:06:18,539 --> 00:06:26,759
and the material—a clash of the sublime and the base, the tragic and the pragmatic. But how do you convey all this

58
00:06:26,759 --> 00:06:34,860
through a single image? With a chicken. This episode, as so often with Dostoevsky, unfolds

59
00:06:34,860 --> 00:06:39,660
rapidly: Verkhovensky has just come in, has just clarified, “So—the intention

60
00:06:39,660 --> 00:06:46,380
still stands? I hope the suicide is still on? The paper—you’ll sign?” And almost without

61
00:06:46,380 --> 00:06:54,240
pausing, he immediately says: “Well! But I notice something over there, on the windowsill, on a plate.” He approaches

62
00:06:54,240 --> 00:06:58,620
“Oh, a chicken boiled with rice! But why is it still untouched? So we’re

63
00:06:58,620 --> 00:07:06,300
in such a state of mind we can’t even touch the chicken…” “I ate,” interrupts

64
00:07:06,300 --> 00:07:12,300
Kirillov, “and it’s none of your business, be silent, of course, it doesn’t matter to me. But

65
00:07:12,300 --> 00:07:19,680
for me, it’s not the same. Imagine, I’ve barely eaten dinner, and so now,

66
00:07:19,680 --> 00:07:27,139
the chicken, I assume, is no longer needed…” Pay attention to how

67
00:07:27,139 --> 00:07:32,340
Kirillov formulates his answer: “Eat, if you can.” Verkhovensky can—oh, he can,

68
00:07:32,340 --> 00:07:39,060
both for himself and for the other guy. “Well, thank you,” he says, and then, “and tea!”

69
00:07:39,060 --> 00:07:43,740
And then it gets even more chilling—the “cherry on the cake” of this scene. Verkhovensky immediately

70
00:07:43,740 --> 00:07:52,580
settled at the table, at the other end of the sofa, and with extraordinary greed attacked the food, but at the same time

71
00:07:52,580 --> 00:07:58,639
kept an eye every moment on his victim. Kirillov stared at him with angry disgust,

72
00:07:58,639 --> 00:08:04,680
motionless, as if unable to break away. Verkhovensky here—he is the triumph of the flesh,

73
00:08:04,680 --> 00:08:09,660
he eats greedily, with appetite, with excitement, as the man a meter away from him is about

74
00:08:09,660 --> 00:08:19,080
to shoot himself—but that means the chicken is up for grabs, too. Note, in this one paragraph, Verkhovensky strips from Kirillov

75
00:08:19,080 --> 00:08:26,520
absolutely everything: his freedom, his last will, his last meal, and, in the end, his life.

76
00:08:26,520 --> 00:08:35,159
The chicken is, of course, just a metaphor, because in essence, Verkhovensky sees people as expendable resources,

77
00:08:35,159 --> 00:08:40,919
matter that feeds his pitiful ambitions and schemes. “Is the happiness of mankind

78
00:08:40,919 --> 00:08:53,279
worth the tear of a child?” asks Ivan Karamazov. “And is the child served with a side, or alone?” clarifies Pyotr

79
00:08:53,279 --> 00:08:59,220
And Kirillov—this strange Kirillov, yes, with his insane idea, but still not an evil

80
00:08:59,220 --> 00:09:03,660
heart—cannot look away. He watches in horror as Verkhovensky devours

81
00:09:03,660 --> 00:09:11,459
the chicken, because he’s not eating only that—he’s also about to “eat” Kirillov

82
00:09:11,459 --> 00:09:17,880
Verkhovensky—the Barabek: ate forty men and a cow, and a bull, and a crooked butcher,

83
00:09:17,880 --> 00:09:27,779
and a cart, and a shaft, and a broom, and a poker, ate the chicken with a side and finished it off. And this whole tangle of contradictions, fears,

84
00:09:27,779 --> 00:09:37,080
and destinies Dostoevsky reveals in a single scene of eating, through the image of a plate of cold chicken with rice.

85
00:09:37,080 --> 00:09:42,060
The eloquent horror of this gastronomic scene was perfectly captured in the legendary

86
00:09:42,060 --> 00:09:46,500
production of “Demons” by the Saint Petersburg Small Drama Theatre, in a six-hour

87
00:09:46,500 --> 00:09:53,640
performance by Lev Dodin, which ran for almost thirty years. Anyone who was lucky enough to see this performance

88
00:09:53,640 --> 00:10:00,180
can no doubt recall Verkhovensky’s scene with the chicken. Once you’ve seen it live,

89
00:10:00,180 --> 00:10:05,660
it’s hard to forget. Here's a fragment of how this scene was played

90
00:10:05,660 --> 00:10:35,519
This is an illustration. In fact, we could end the discussion of today’s

91
00:10:35,519 --> 00:10:42,660
fragment here, if not for one detail. The point is, this contrast—refusal to eat versus gluttony as a metaphor

92
00:10:42,660 --> 00:10:47,760
for value conflict—is found in a book Dostoevsky greatly

93
00:10:47,760 --> 00:10:52,620
admired. A book that influenced all his major works, about which he

94
00:10:52,620 --> 00:10:59,040
once said that nowhere in the world is there a work deeper or stronger. And finally, a book

95
00:10:59,040 --> 00:11:04,500
we’ve already mentioned today—of course, Cervantes’s “Don Quixote.” Remember how

96
00:11:04,500 --> 00:11:08,640
the relationship between Don Quixote and Sancho Panza is built in the first volume? We talked

97
00:11:08,640 --> 00:11:14,220
about this in one of the early episodes of “Armen and Fyodor” dedicated to that novel. Sancho

98
00:11:14,220 --> 00:11:21,000
is obsessed with food, constantly reminding Quixote about meals. At every opportunity, he tries to eat,

99
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:27,240
regardless of his master’s state—whether he's preaching, fasting, or suffering.

100
00:11:27,240 --> 00:11:33,480
And the great American director Orson Welles, in his “Don Quixote,” which, by a

101
00:11:33,480 --> 00:11:42,959
remarkable coincidence, will be released almost simultaneously with Dodin’s production, depicts a scene uncannily reminiscent of

102
00:11:42,959 --> 00:11:50,160
this episode from “Demons”: there, Sancho Panza, before the fasting eyes of Quixote, will greedily devour

103
00:11:50,160 --> 00:12:20,120
—what do you think? Of course—a chicken. [music] I want this, for Marina to

104
00:12:20,120 --> 00:12:36,180
It only remains to clarify that in spirit, this episode completely matches Cervantes’s “Don Quixote,” but as for the letter—

105
00:12:36,180 --> 00:12:43,019
not entirely: in the text of the novel, there’s no scene with chicken quite like this. Still,

106
00:12:43,019 --> 00:12:51,720
in the end, it's easy to explain: Cervantes never read Dostoevsky, whereas Orson Welles did.

107
00:12:51,720 --> 00:12:58,860
This is Armen and Fyodor’s literary channel and the “Episode” section. I hope our experiment with this new concise

108
00:12:58,860 --> 00:13:03,540
format was a success. If so, please let us know in the comments which other

109
00:13:03,540 --> 00:13:28,380
episodes you’d like to see in this section in the future. For now—that’s all. My name is Armen. Until next time! [music
.